<module>
  <title>toponymic name-descriptions</title>
  <p>Toponymic name-descriptions are <a href="?xx=nouns/name_descriptions">name-descriptions</a> which are also <a href="?xx=nouns/toponyms">toponyms</a>, 
    i.e. they are definite common noun phrases used to name places and other geographical entities.</p>
  <p>Like other name-descriptions, toponymic name-descriptions can be classified into two <u>grammatical</u> types –</p>
  <ul>
    <li><u>pre-specified</u> toponymic name-descriptions 
      eg. <m>An t-Eilean Dubh</m> <en>The Black Isle</en>, <m>A’ Chomraich</m> <en>Applecross</en>, <m>An Fhraing</m> <en>France</en>, 
      <m>Na h-Ìnnseachan</m> <en>India</en>,
      <m>Am Monadh Ruadh</m> <en>The Cairngorms</en>, <m>An Linne Latharnach</m> <en>The Lorne Firth</en></li>
    <li><u>post-specified</u> toponymic name-descriptions 
      eg. <m>Eilean nam Muc</m> <en>Muck</en>, <m>Baile Ùr an t-Slèibhe</m> <en>Newtonmore</en>, 
      <m>Dùthaich MhicAoidh</m> <en>North Sutherland</en>, <m>Innis Tìle</m> <en>Iceland</en>, <m>Beinn a’ Bhreacaidh</m> <en>Ben Vrackie</en>, <m>Loch Obha</m> <en>Loch Awe</en>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>Like other toponyms, toponymic name-descriptions can be classified <u>semantically</u> according to the kind of geographical entity they refer to –</p>
  <ul>
    <li>islands and districts eg. <i>An t-Eilean Dubh</i>, <i>Eilean nam Muc</i>, <i>Dùthaich MhicAoidh</i> <boxlink ref="#districts"/></li>
    <li>towns and settlements eg. <i>A’ Chomraich</i>, <i>Baile Ùr an t-Slèibhe</i> <boxlink ref="#settlements"/></li>
    <li>countries and continents eg. <i>An Fhraing</i>, <i>Na h-Ìnnseachan</i>, <i>Innis Tìle</i> <boxlink ref="#countries"/></li>
    <li>mountains and uplands eg. <i>Beinn a’ Bhreacaidh</i>, <i>Am Monadh Ruadh</i></li>
    <li>rivers, lakes and seas eg. <i>An Linne Latharnach</i>, <i>Loch Obha</i>  <boxlink ref="#water"/></li>
  </ul>
  
